content.description: The crux is right at the base pulling over the overhang and feels stiff for the grade.  Hint: put your right foot on the right seam.  Stab for the nice finger jamb above then jamb the continuous fingercrack up to the anchor.
content.protection:
Cams to 2.5" with extra in the finger to micro size

50 meter rope
content.location: The obvious fingercrack on the left side of the formation.

content.description:
Who would expect to find a wild overhanging sport route in this area?

Scramble to the top of a block to clip the first bolt under the overhang.  From here, big juggy moves take you up and left (some heel hooking chops might come in handy here).  You find yourself under a massive hueco into which you can crawl for a rest before popping back out onto the overhanging wall, and up over the lip.
content.protection: 3 bolts provide good protection.  An alternate start could be protected with some trad gear.
content.location: Left of Z-Crack, around the corner and a bit uphill.

content.description:
Jam up the handcrack through a bulge to a ledge. Above this is the crux, a short but strenuous overhanging fist crack section. Finish to the anchor on the much easier handcrack.

A variation at the bottom is a left-leaning crack (5.10+), cleaned in 2014 by Geoff Georges. At the top of this variation, traverse back right to upper Meat Grinder.
content.protection:
2 each cams from 1" to 3.5"

50 meter rope
content.location: The obvious hand and fist crack in the center of the formation.

climbs.name: Jaws of Life
climbs.fa: Matt Kerns 1991; arete start Mack Johnson 1993

content.description: Start up a moderate crack, then maneuver up the hanging arête past 2 bolts to a rest.  Up the technical face to the top.
content.protection: 3 bolts, small cams to 1".  Anchors on top or walk off.
content.location: Right of St Vitus's Dance, left of Z-Crack.  The original line traversed in from the start of St. Vitus.

climbs.name: Hind Quarters
climbs.fa: Chumstick Joe, 2001 (1st lead, previously TRed by others)

content.description:
A fun, granite face climb with some varied moves.

Start up on big holds with fun liebacking from flakes to a good rest just under the fourth bolt. Crimps and thin feet are the crux while getting past the fourth bolt.

Climbing through the fifth and six bolts is additional fun using some larger-but-not-entirely-positive holds. Good balance will see it through.
content.location:
The bolted line to the right of the very obvious

Dogleg Crack

. Hike to the right past the face containing

Z Crack

and up the hill a bit to the base of

Dogleg Crack

and

Hind Quarters

.

content.description: Start out by scrambling up the dihedral to gain the base of the finger to thin hand crack.  Jamb this to the top.  The crux section is in the first 15 feet of the crack, above that it is 5.7.
content.protection:
2 each cams from finger sized to a #2 camalot

50 meter rope
content.location: The obvious right leaning slabby handcrack on the right (north) side of the formation.

content.description: Short sport climb up the prow on the right.
content.location: Right side of the jutting prow to the right of main Alphabet Rock.

climbs.name: Alphabet Soup
climbs.fa: FA Mack Johnson, James Ellis, Reed O'Brien 2011

content.description: Start in a crack to the right of Meat Grinder. Climb up this around a bulge and onto a ledge, then up a little higher to a finger traverse left that joins the top of Meat Grinder.
Alternate finish to Z-Crack.Climb that route to its final section, then traverse left to a thin seam.
content.protection:
Whatever you would bring on Z-Crack, plus an extra .75, 1, and .2.

RP's and Slider nuts fit at the crux but are hard to place
content.location: Toprope from Jaws of Life anchors, or the Z-Crack anchors.
